As the epidemic spread, the atmosphere in Wuhan became tense and the original plan was disrupted. On New Year's Eve, he and his family drove 1,300 kilometers back to Shenzhen, the days of home quarantine.
He came up with the idea of collecting photos of ordinary people living in their homes. He called the project "the daily life of 1,000 Chinese families during the epidemic of boxer plague" , "As a witness to this great event, I want to leave us ordinary people with our daily lives. "
In the photos, there are incomplete family photos: the wife is a doctor, this Spring Festival has been fighting the epidemic front, no vacation; the epidemic blocked some people's way home, the 92-year-old grandmother only through video chat with his grandson; An 85-year-old man stays at home, gets up at six every day, from the bedroom to the kitchen, back and forth eight times. Most of all, she asked, "what time is it? ". "She said all she could do now was wait, wait for spring to Bloom" ..
These trivial life, presents the warmth which is often ignored by us, in this special period, the Chinese people have to accept the reality of the epidemic, and with an optimistic, tenacious attitude to fight the epidemic of the day-to-day state.

Editor Hu Daqi, Lu Meng

I have lived in Shenzhen for 28 years. Almost every Spring Festival, I take my family back to my hometown in Xiangyang, Hubei Province. A few years ago, I often take the elderly to the warm Spring Festival in Shenzhen, but as the elderly get older, they do not want to toss about, we had to keep running home.

January 18,2020, the Chinese New Year, we set out early in the morning. The journey from Shenzhen to Xiangyang is more than 1,300 km and, based on past self-driving experience, takes 17 or 18 hours. This year, it took 20 hours to cover just 400 kilometers in Guangdong. It took 38 hours. Looking back, behind the huge and congested traffic, there are people like me who want to return home.

Xiangyang is a beautiful old city. When I got home on January 20, just four days before the New Year's Eve, I accompanied my in-laws to the wholesale market to buy some New Year's Eve products, to the flower market to buy two potted flowers, and to take my parents to the new Xiangyang East station to have a look. It's a brand new high speed rail station that opened in 2019. The 90-year-old father-in-law was delighted.

Amid the usual atmosphere of peace, disquieting news ensued, first on January 20, when Zhong Nanshan confirmed that human to human transmission had COVID-19, and then on New Year's Eve, when Wuhan suddenly declared the city closed. That has raised tensions in Xiangyang, some 300km from Wuhan. His father-in-law, an old revolutionary soldier, acted decisively and immediately cancelled the reunion dinner he had ordered at the hotel. New Year's Eve at home group year, the two old let us eat as soon as possible to leave. They can take care of themselves.

So, on New Year's Eve, the traditional Chinese day for Family Reunion, I hurried to drive 1300 kilometers to "escape" back to Shenzhen. On January 25, the day after I left Xiangyang, the city also imposed some traffic controls. Train stations in Xiangyang were closed on January 27, ferries were suspended on January 28 and the city was sealed off in Xiangyang.

On the first day of the New Year back to Shenzhen, we did not go home, first went to the community declaration, and entered the home 14 days of self-isolation period.

The experience of running away on New Year's Eve, for the first time in my life, was also very uncomfortable for me. Like most Chinese, staying home is a contribution to the fight against the disease. But instead of taking my temperature and reporting it to the community every day, I had to go online and watch the epidemic unfold. I can't sit around the house all day, consumed by anxiety. Therefore, the idea of collecting photos from ordinary people on the Internet came into being, and the project was named as "everyday life of 1000 families in China during the epidemic period of Heptagon" .

In the call for proposals, i wrote: "As witnesses to this great event, we also hope to leave behind us ordinary people in the big event of life, because each of us is a part of this history, together with the Spring Festival of the boxer year, will give us unforgettable memories. "

The idea has the full support of Mr. David Rowe and his new media platform windface photography. Netizens and numerous photographers and institutions all over the country responded and took part, with 16,000 people participating in just one week.

Selected from a vast collection of photographs, the participants recorded this special period from different perspectives, forcing Chinese people to accept the reality of the epidemic and to fight against it with optimism and tenacity in their daily lives.

Not that I'm terribly worried, 10 years of backpacking, some experience, no panic when things go wrong, the only thing that bothers me is living with my parents, knowing that it's impossible to be completely disconnected from them, sELF-COMFORT: I will not be affected. I have been concerned about the train ride whether there is a confirmed case, check no, such as take a pill to calm down.

During the home quarantine, the community workers are very responsible, every day call to ask if the body is not feeling well, and video, said home what needs community can help solve. Every few days, the community sent me the daily food I need, put on the door to tell. Home Isolation these days, I cook at home every day, my mother also praised me.

I dare not and will not easily believe it, but I have to believe that the epidemic is pulling down our fig leaf piece by piece, not all good is good, I firmly believe that the world of cause and effect, Time will prove.

All this time, the camera seemed to be moving away from me, like a ten-layer mask, making a sound so far away, the real us so weak, reflecting on the disaster, fearing for life, I chose to respect. Some of these portraits are selfies, some are pet pictures, some are animated designs, some are simply photoshopped masks on the original portraits, and some wear masks on famous paintings or scenic spots.

Boredom at home gives people plenty of time to be creative and express complex and diverse attitudes about resisting the virus. Including the boring me, to pick friends of these wechat pictures. To tell the truth, pick these avatars is not involved in "theft" I do not know in the heart, after all, can not give the host one by one call. All of US SAY WE'RE SORRY! If you see a picture of you and you don't want it, please tell me to take it down.

In addition, the work portraits of the anti-flu angels collected online were used to surround the masked wechat images as a tribute to them. It was their tenacity and even sacrifice in the face of the virus, so that the vast majority of people at home to ensure safety.

The epidemic is not over, life still continues, "thousands of households as 1000 Chinese families day-to-day Gengzi epidemic period, " photo collection is also ongoing.
